    "summary": "The Long March of 1934–1935 was the epic strategic retreat of the Chinese Communist Party's Red Army, covering approximately 9,000 kilometers through some of China's most remote and treacherous terrain to escape encirclement by Nationalist Kuomintang forces. Beginning in October 1934 from the Jiangxi Soviet in southeastern China, some 86,000 troops set out on a march that would take over a year and pass through eleven provinces, crossing eighteen mountain ranges and twenty-four rivers.\n\nThe human cost was catastrophic: only around 8,000 to 10,000 of those who set out completed the march to Yan'an in northern Shaanxi province. The march was also the crucible in which Mao Zedong's leadership of the Communist Party was consolidated, particularly at the Zunyi Conference in January 1935, where he was elevated to preeminent military command. Despite the terrible losses, Communist propaganda transformed the Long March into a founding myth of extraordinary heroism and endurance that legitimized Mao's leadership and the party's claim to represent the Chinese people.\n\nThe Long March preserved the Communist Party from destruction and allowed it to regroup, recruit in new territories, and ultimately prevail in the [[event:2710|Chinese Civil War]] fourteen years later. It remains one of the defining events in Chinese Communist revolutionary mythology, taught to successive generations as an exemplary story of revolutionary sacrifice and perseverance.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Long_March",
